title: Endgame spoilers
body:
educatedinyellow replied to your post “Endgame Spoilers”
I also didn’t like the way they turned Thor’s trauma into a running joke, I thought that was ill-advised. He was so much more interesting and compelling in “Infinity War,” whereas he felt cartoonish in “Endgame.” But, even though all of us have our own quibbles, I thought the movie worked incredibly well at bringing so many characters and such a huge story to a satisfying conclusion. I especially loved how they handled Tony’s story. A worthy goodbye to a great character!

I agree it was a fantastic story. And although Tony’s death made perfect sense narratively speaking, it still devastated me because he was my favorite MCU character. Part of me wishes he could have quietly retired after all of this, with Pepper and Morgan and live happily ever after. I mean, why not?? Clint gets that. 

I’m also still bitter about the fact that apparently Loki is gone for good

summary: A credits stinger for Avengers: Endgame. SPOILERS.
title: A credits stinger for Avengers: Endgame. SPOILERS.
body:
(SPOILERS. SERIOUSLY.)

~~~

*Kick off the wall. Use gravity to break his hold.*

*Free yourself. Make your own choice.*

*Don’t let him see your fear. Don’t make him bear that burden, too.*

Wind whistling in her ears, nearly blocking the howl of grief.

Holding her friends in her heart as a bulwark against the fear.

Trusting Clint to understand someday. Knowing Steve would…but Bruce wouldn’t.

Regretting that she’d had so little time with Okoye and Carol.

Falling to bring back Wanda, Shuri, Nick and Sam, as much as she fell to bring back Laura, Lilah, Connor, and Nathaniel. And every unnamed person who’d disappeared with them.

And then no more wind, no more fear, no more falling.

She jumped to have a chance to bring them back. She could be the sacrifice, not just because she wanted to, but because she was the only person left Clint loved. And she loved Clint too much to let him miss the chance to get his family back. She loved Steve and Bruce, Okoye and Carol, she loved the world. She willingly sent herself to her death for them all. Just for a chance.

A moment later, warmth. The icy wind of Vormir no longer cutting through her bones. A soft droning in her ears.

…Bees. Those are bees.

A faint, sweet scent - hydrangeas and honeysuckle.

Under her back, solid ground, grass tickling her ear.

For a moment, she thinks this is the last firing of her synapses, a dream of peace and home before she finally dies.

But

it

doesn’t

end.

She blinks. Opens her eyes to a green leafy canopy above. Reaching to her head, no injury, just a jagged scar down the back of her scalp. Hair still braided, still wearing the same clothing.

She lurches upright when she hears voices and stares wildly around. The white board house, the open fields, the small barn down the hill…

The archery target on the tree beside her.

A screen door slams open. For a moment, she doesn’t recognize the girl. But the girl recognizes her and screams for her father.

She rolls herself onto her feet and suddenly - Lilah.

Behind her, Clint.

Clint staggers into the yard, falls to his knees next to her. Shakily, he touches her hand. “Nat?”

Nat. Natalie Rushman. Natasha Romanova. The Black Widow. Graduate of the Red Room. Leader of the Avengers these past 5 years.

She settles back into herself suddenly. She looks AT Clint sharply, leaning forward. “It worked.” A moment later she is at the center of the whole Barton family, crying and hugging. She is home.

~end

(The idea is that when Steve returns the Soul Stone to Vormir, the exchange is the same - a soul for the stone, so the stone for a soul.)

((They did Nat wrong and I want to fix it.))

(((Clint’s her family. She talks about the Avengers or SHIELD as her family, Steve is her best friend, she has a thing for Bruce, but Clint is her family. She was still wearing the arrow necklace in Endgame. Clint is her family.))))

((((Clint is Natasha’s family.))))

trail.content_raw:
(SPOILERS. SERIOUSLY.)

~~~

*Kick off the wall. Use gravity to break his hold.*

*Free yourself. Make your own choice.*

*Don’t let him see your fear. Don’t make him bear that burden, too.*

Wind whistling in her ears, nearly blocking the howl of grief.

Holding her friends in her heart as a bulwark against the fear.

Trusting Clint to understand someday. Knowing Steve would…but Bruce wouldn’t.

Regretting that she’d had so little time with Okoye and Carol.

Falling to bring back Wanda, Shuri, Nick and Sam, as much as she fell to bring back Laura, Lilah, Connor, and Nathaniel. And every unnamed person who’d disappeared with them.

And then no more wind, no more fear, no more falling.

She jumped to have a chance to bring them back. She could be the sacrifice, not just because she wanted to, but because she was the only person left Clint loved. And she loved Clint too much to let him miss the chance to get his family back. She loved Steve and Bruce, Okoye and Carol, she loved the world. She willingly sent herself to her death for them all. Just for a chance.

A moment later, warmth. The icy wind of Vormir no longer cutting through her bones. A soft droning in her ears.

…Bees. Those are bees.

A faint, sweet scent - hydrangeas and honeysuckle.

Under her back, solid ground, grass tickling her ear.

For a moment, she thinks this is the last firing of her synapses, a dream of peace and home before she finally dies.

But

it

doesn’t

end.

She blinks. Opens her eyes to a green leafy canopy above. Reaching to her head, no injury, just a jagged scar down the back of her scalp. Hair still braided, still wearing the same clothing.

She lurches upright when she hears voices and stares wildly around. The white board house, the open fields, the small barn down the hill…

The archery target on the tree beside her.

A screen door slams open. For a moment, she doesn’t recognize the girl. But the girl recognizes her and screams for her father.

She rolls herself onto her feet and suddenly - Lilah.

Behind her, Clint.

Clint staggers into the yard, falls to his knees next to her. Shakily, he touches her hand. “Nat?”

Nat. Natalie Rushman. Natasha Romanova. The Black Widow. Graduate of the Red Room. Leader of the Avengers these past 5 years.

She settles back into herself suddenly. She looks AT Clint sharply, leaning forward. “It worked.” A moment later she is at the center of the whole Barton family, crying and hugging. She is home.

~end
